entry.content:
- Adds a feature & flag to allow sharing the page content with CSC. The

user still has to enable the preference in settings or the opt-in

before sharing page content. Enabling the feature/flag alone isn't

sufficient. Disabling the feature/flag after enabling the preference

will stop sharing page content. So users who were in the enabled group

previously but left won't be stuck sharing page content without an the

ability to disable it.

enabled.



- Updates callsites in `CompanionUrlBuilder` that share the URL and were

previously checking if sharing page content was allowed to instead

check if sharing URL is allowed. Before, checking either was

equivalent.



- Makes allowing the opt-in enable the pref.



- Refreshes the CSC frame when the pref changes.

entry.title: Network service: Note that `request_initiator` is a spec request origin
entry.content:
FedCM and CORS integration has been discussed in

https://github.com/fedidcg/FedCM/issues/428, among other places, and

various flavors of the discussion revealed confusion around both the

kNoCors request mode in the implementation and spec, as well as the

`network::ResourceRequest::request_initiator`, and how it relates to the

Fetch Standard.



Some folks didn't realize that `request_initiator`, when used by the

web platform specifically, was equivalent to a Fetch request's origin

[1], so this CL helps clear this up.



[1]: https://fetch.spec.whatwg.org/#concept-request-origin

entry.title: Revert "Add a high priority queue for sync cookie calls in the network service"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a922565736a5f5f691c3596215fe9e6cdc365940.



Reason for revert: This did not show any improvement.



Original change's description:

> Add a high priority queue for sync cookie calls in the network service

>

> This change adds a minimal scheduler for the network service thread

> which has a default task queue and high priority task queue. The

> RestrictedCookieManager interface will be bound using the high priority

> task queue, which should make the sync cookie accesses/writes from the

> renderer faster if there are other tasks that need to be run in the

> network service.

>

> The hope is that re-ordering these tasks with other network tasks will

> not be a problem since they are generally called as sync calls from the

> renderer. If there turns out to be problems with this later we can

> revisit how tasks are prioritized.

entry.title: Correct fragmentation of floats inside inlines.
entry.content:
If layout decided to fragment a float, or break before it, and this

float was inside an inline formatting context, it would "escape" the

inline formatting context for subsequent fragments, and be laid out as a

direct float child of the containing block. This would cause paint and

hit testing issues, because the actual inline ancestors of the float

would have no effect on the float, so that e.g. a SPAN with relative

positioning or opacity would only affect the first fragment of the

float. Furthermore, the fact that we were not keeping the float inside

the inline formatting context could also result in a non-contiguous

FragmentData range for a LayoutInline, and, if this LayoutInline

established a PaintLayer, we would get confused and fail to paint /

hit-test anything in a after a tall float.



We already had code to propagate float breaks to the containing block

layout algorithm. The fix is to wrap the break tokens of such floats

inside an inline break token, and resume such inline break tokens as

parallel fragmentation flows.



We had code in PrePaint as an attempt to cope with escaping float

fragments, to some extent, which is no longer required, so I removed it.

It should be noted that this did by no means work in all situations. If

a float was a child of a PaintLayer-establishing LayoutInline, PrePaint

would get confused as to which PaintLayer was the containing layer of

the float.



More cleanup is possible after this. For now, added a note to

NGBoxFragmentPainter::PaintFloatingChildren(). We should now be able to

assume non-contiguous ranges of physical fragments that have fragment

items. Previously, a tall and fragmented float could prevent some of the

containing physical fragments from getting items.



Update two unit tests. DumpFragmentTree() unfortunately doesn't dump the

contents of a line box, so now that resumed floats also end up inside

lines, they aren't dumped. This was already the case for the first

fragment of any float in an inline formatting context, but now it also

happens to subsequent fragments.

entry.title: [StyleBuilder] Remove [Raw]DataRef
entry.content:
These wrappers no longer serve any important purpose, and is mostly

just in the way of future development. This CL removes DataRef and

RawDataRef, and instead uses UncompressedMember and raw pointers

(respectively).



Accessing (i.e. mutating) fields now happen via nested Access calls.

E.g. to access X->Y->Z, we previously did:



X.Access(x_bit)->Y.Access(y_bit)->Z = ...



Whereas now we do:



Access(Access(X, x_bit)->Y, y_bit)->Z = ...



This is arguably less readable, but also not very important, since

clients of ComputedStyle do not interact directly with this code.



Some minor cleanup to ComputedStyleAccessFlags: we don't need a name

for this struct anymore, since all the flags are once again only

relevant within the builder.



The style perf test appears neutral (Alder Lake).

entry.title: Remove *-archive-dbg builders in favor of other main waterfall builders

The *-archive-dbg builders don't do any archiving, and mostly serve to

platforms + also clobber. There are other is_debug=true builders,

removes all the *-archive-dbg builders in favor of their duplicates.

(dbg)", and the latter is switched to compiling "all" and has

its reclient -Js bumped to match the former. This will have a large

increase in cycle time on "Android arm Builder (dbg)", but it doesn't

trigger any child testers, so it won't be delaying any of those. And

if it needs to speed back-up, we can re-use the machine resources

freed-up here to beef it up.

and the latter has its reclient -Js bumped to match the former.

entry.title: view-transition: Rename GetActiveTransition to GetTransition
entry.content:
The level 2 spec defines what it means to "activate" a view transition:

https://drafts.csswg.org/css-view-transitions-1/#activate-view-transition

This implies an "active" transition is one that's running on the

destination state of the page. (i.e. capturing elements or playing

the animation)



However GetActiveTransition returns an existing non-finished transition

which is a different meaning from the one in the spec.



This CL renames GetActiveTransition to GetTransition so that "active"

can be used for the meaning defined by the spec.

entry.title: Use simple approach to invalidating aria-hidden subtrees
entry.content:
A general optimization for Chrome was landed in CL:4687538, which

invalidated cached values individual nodes rather than the entire

document, for small changes and updates to the layout and DOM.



However, aria-hidden changes require entire subtrees to be invalidated.

There are a couple of approaches that could work. The one taken

in the landing of CL:4687538 was to attempt to iterate the tree

while invalidating the objects. However, this led to an infinite

loop as invalidating cached objects affects tree walking.



A simpler approach is to reuse another method that works well,

RemoveSubtreeWhenSafe(). This wipes out the entire aria-hidden

subtree of AXObjects and recreates it. As aria-hidden is not

expected to change very often, this is believed to be performant

enough. In addition, this results in being able to remove

InvalidateCachedValuesOnSubtree() from the codebase, resulting

in simpler, cleaner code.



Fixed: 1484425

entry.title: Rename multipage printing test files
entry.content:
Some printing tests rely upon the input having multiple pages, and they

require knowing the exact number of pages that are specified in the

input. Chrome uses very simple HTML files which have a single line of

text with page breaks to provide this, so that each line will be a

separate page.



In most tests that need more than one page, the tests have used

multipage.html, which has 3 pages. Tests for N-up have used

multipagenup.html, which has 7 pages. Note that there is nothing

specific about N-up in this input file other than the name; it is just

historically named this way because N-up testing that a works better

when there are more than just 3 pages.



Shutdown processing could benefit from also using a multipage test case

with more than 3 pages. Since shutdown logic has nothing to do with

N-up, using a test input of multipagenup.html feels awkward.



The multipage and multipagenup names do not fully reflect their

contents, even though tests are hard-coded with expectations that they

have 3 and 7 pages respectively.



Rename these files to reflect that they are intended to provide a

specifiic number of pages. This makes existing tests clearer, as well

as paving the way for the 7 page test file to be reused in contexts

other than N-up without confusion.

entry.title: Set origin to commit for data: URLs
entry.content:
We need to set the origin_to_commit for data: URLs as part of the

transition to removing source SiteInstance from RenderFrameProxyHost.

Because data: URLs have opaque origins, we cannot identify which data:

URL is the source SiteInstance if there are multiple data: SiteInstances

in a group. By using the origin_to_commit, we can compare origin nonces

to make sure we use the correct data: URL SiteInstance as the source

SiteInstance.



We want the browser and renderer side nonces to match. Without this change, the

renderer calculates its own opaque origin, which will differ from the origin

used on the browser side to create a data: SiteInstance. If the browser and

renderer side origins don't match, we can't use it to identify a data: URL

SiteInstance.



We do not include LoadDataWithBaseUrl cases with a base URL because we don't

need SiteInstanceGroup in those cases. The base URL will be used to determine

the SiteInstance. If the base URL is empty, then the URL is treated like a

regular data: URL.



Bug: 1447896, 1291351

entry.title: Add base::ScopedTempFile
entry.content:
ScopedTempFile aims to replace ad-hoc classes that duplicate this

functionality such as system_media_controls::internal::ScopedFile [1]

and ResourceFile [2].



Some alternatives were considered:

* Reuse ScopedTempDir

- Have ScopedTempDir handle files too. Surprisingly, the only code

that's reusable would be Take() and GetPath(). Everything else

needs conditional logic depending on if a file or directory is

used. See [3] for my attempt at this. Additionally,

ScopedTempDir would need to be renamed to something like

ScopedTempPath, and ScopedTempDir is currently used in 1,524 files.

* Don't add ScopedTempFile

- Use ScopedTempDir instead. This isn't ideal due to the additional

system call overhead.

- Live with the status quo. Not ideal due to duplication.

entry.title: [webauthn] Add platform authenticator button if it can't enumerate creds
entry.content:
With the new passkey get assertion UI, platform authenticator

credentials are listed in the mechanism selection screen, so we don't

show a dedicated button to dispatch to the platform authenticator.

Unfortunately, the ChromeOS platform authenticator can report the

availability of credentials but not enumerate them, so there is no way

to trigger it with the new UI.



This CL fixes this bug by bringing back the "This device" button to

dispatch to the platform authenticator when credentials are reported to

be available but not enumerated.
